This is the problem that Bitcoin solved. We should embrace it, for the sake of humanity's freedom. Trading altcoins is not interesting compared to this.
A free-market altcoin that is centralised, even if it did get large enough to threaten central banks, can be shut down, because they are centralised.

An altcoin, with a group of "nerds" controlling the consensus and the premine, are always centralised, and are therefore not competing with Bitcoin to overthrow fiat for a position as the dominant free-market money. The nerds are just different Central Bankers.
Then there is the question of altcoins. They are actually not alternatives to Bitcoin, because Bitcoin is replacing the centralised proof-of-stake fiat system controlled by Central Banks.
So this should not be used as an argument against the thesis that one day, bitcoin will replace these fiat currencies, and will be the only one that survives the evolution process of the free market.

This led to the elimination of gold backing from these IOUs (fiat money). (in 1971, President Nixon)  We now have worthless pieces of paper, also in digital form, that we are forced to use by law, not the free market.

So you see, we already have a precedent for “one” money evolving from many.   Then, because gold was difficult to transport, and paper IOUs were used as a replacement, solving gold’s portability problem, this made a sacrifice with centralisation.

These entities hold a very large percentage of the total #BTC supply and they are not selling even with near term volatility and drawdowns.  This is a #bull market.

Overall, the Mean Coin Age and Miner Reserves helps identify the trend and activity of important holders of #BTC. The strong trend in accumulation of LTHs and Miners continuing to maintain reserves is a very bullish signal for #Bitcoin.

There are no signs of major distribution in miners which suggests miners continue to expect #BTC to appreciate in value in the coming months. If this was a bear market, we would have seen tens of thousands of #BTC sold with reserves trending lower. Reserves continue to hold.
Miner outflows to exchanges to sell have been very low compared to major selling activity in late 2020 and early 2021 where 10,000 to 40,000 #BTC were moved.

Here’s the 2021 bull market. The overall trend this year has shown Miners are in net accumulation and have no interest in selling #BTC at current prices. Miners accumulated when #BTC was consolidating at 30k. Reserves continue to hold and slowly trend higher.  https://t.co/DYM1XtYNIo

2017 Bull market showed Miners distributing as #BTC appreciated. This can be expected as Miners are incentivized to sell when there is rapid price appreciation. The 2018 bear market squeezed out miners as price fell significantly. Miners sold under pressure.  https://t.co/sBnxfqyqcO
This is one of many Onchain metrics that show the overall trend is still bullish and that #BTC is likely in a bull market.

MCA has been trending higher for 4 months, showing a firm trend of accumulation in long term holders. If this was a bear market, we would have seen significant distribution after the initial 55% crash. LTHs instead strongly accumulated #BTC pushing MCA higher.

Here’s the 2021 Bull market. LTHs were distributing during the run up from January to May, but the 55% crash did not cause LTHs to continue distributing. MCA actually trended higher confirming LTH re-accumulation while BTC consolidated at 30k.  https://t.co/i7EXpIRf8s

BTC consolidated for around 6 to 7 months causing the Mean Coin Age to trend higher as long term holders entered re-accumulation. Once price started rapidly rising, the Mean Coin Age started to fall, confirming long term holders started to distribute and take profit.  https://t.co/U2QTmg3izn

This occurred after the initial 2013 peak, as long term holders distributed as price went parabolic. After price made the first peak, BTC had a deep correction which led to long term holders entering re-accumulation.

For example, in the 2017 bull market, long term holders distributed as price went parabolic, and continued to distribute after the peak, as BTC entered the 2018 bear market. Mean Coin Age continued to fall confirming long term holders were distributing.  https://t.co/TzMOq52ZxL

Watching Mean Coin Age metric and Miners is a great way to measure the trend of accumulation or distribution in #BTC long term holders.  Here’s a thread taking a look at previous bull and bear markets:  https://t.co/zJL7CgplVC

In Bitcoin miners use hash power to bid on newly created BTC. The block reward is constant, but the price is not. In Meter miners convert their hash power to mine MTR, where the price is constant but block rewards are variable based on total network hash power.

Following on from yesterday, how does MTR maintain stability?   Each MTR is created with 10 kWh of electricity using SHA256 Proof of Work, the same method as BTC. Miners profit chasing behavior ties the cost of global competitive electricity price to the value of MTR.
